<section id="slide-org8538a73">
<h3 id="org8538a73"><span class="section-number-3">2.3</span> Joint Distribution</h3>
<p>
Some function H with a domain on \mathbb{R}<sup>2</sup>
</p>

<ol>
<li>\(H\) is 2-increasing</li>
<li>Is grounded</li>
<li>\(H\left(x,-\infty\right)=H\left(y,-\infty\right)=0\)</li>
<li>\(H\left(\infty,\infty\right)=1\)</li>

</ol>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4b80bf3">
<h3 id="org4b80bf3"><span class="section-number-3">2.4</span> Quasi Inverse</h3>

<div id="orgc033766" class="figure">
<p><object type="image/svg+xml" data="../media/quasi-inverse.svg" class="org-svg" width="400px">
Sorry, your browser does not support SVG.</object>
</p>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org05dc4e8">
<h2 id="org05dc4e8"><span class="section-number-2">3</span> Sklar's Theorem</h2>
<p>
We can always find a copula \(C\):
\[
    H\left(x,y\right)=C\left(F\left(x\right),\text{G\ensuremath{\left(y\right)}}\right)
  \]
</p>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgaa27f5e">
<h3 id="orgaa27f5e"><span class="section-number-3">3.1</span> Finding that Copula</h3>
<p>
Just inverse it:
\[
    C\left(u,v\right)=H\left(F^{-1}\left(x\right),G^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)
   \]
</p>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb4eb837">
<h3 id="orgb4eb837"><span class="section-number-3">3.2</span> Marginals of the Copula</h3>
<p>
The marginals of this copula will be uniformly distributed.
</p>
</section>
</section>
